segments.text: And so in each case, the students then live right by the buildings themselves.
Right.
And they have most of their informal student life in their college, not all of it alone.
The cafeteria, the lounges, the ice cream parlors, the bookstore, and so forth.
The sundry store.
One thing that hasn't worked out is the ratio of undergraduates to graduates.
mostly undergraduates, only about 1,500 graduates.
That's including the medical school inscription institution.
And I don't know quite why that is, but it has... Well, certainly one powerful reason is the lack of academic jobs.
Another is that
They just don't have money to support them.
Traditionally, you should support all your graduate students.
They don't have enough teaching assistantships or enough research assistantships to support any more graduate students.
But maybe there's something more fundamental.
I won't even back it.
I've been away 12 years.
I've only been back a few months.
And I'm a slow learner.
And I don't really understand what's happening.

The other thing which I guess bothers me is that the collegiate spirit, the collegial spirit which is so characteristic of Harvard, where the tradition is that all faculty members help each other out, doesn't exist here.
faculty members do help each other out in the sense that if I have to go on a trip, somebody will take my class.
Sort of like a mother cow, take care of other people's, other cows' calves, as long as he doesn't have to nurse them.
But the life of the, the intellectual life
of intellectual interchange between different parts of the university that I don't think exists very much.
It's more like Berkeley than it is like Harvard.
I don't know why that is.
There are some faculty members who are enthusiastic about increasing and improving intellectual and social interchange.
These are dedicated, idealistic type guys.
And they include the chancellor.
The chancellor himself doesn't, he's a pretty remote figure.
And I think if I were a chancellor, I'd spend at least 50% of my time wandering around the universe and talking to people, as I used to do when I was director of scripts.
which I learned from Columbus Islin, who preceded me as director of Woods Hole by about 10 years.
I more or less patterned myself after him in terms of how I behaved with members of the staff.
Always trying to find out what people were doing and why they were doing it and being more interested in what they were doing than anybody else.
And I was talking to them that they were the chief guy in the world.
It was very important to me.
Yeah.
Do you think Scripps has grown too large?
I don't know.
What do you think?
I don't know.
I just wonder.
I wonder if there's an optimal place where an institution or a university becomes so large it's difficult to have an interchange of ideas.
Well, I'll tell you one thing.
This is discouraging to me.
I was reading about it in the minutes of the script staff meeting.
When I was a graduate student, it was traditional that we had a staff lunch once a week, where somebody would talk about his research.
And Sperger kept that up, and I kept it up.
And I always went myself.
And sort of made it quite clear that this is what everybody's supposed to do.
This custom has gone into abeyance the last four or five years.
They tried to revive it this year.
And as a result of a questionnaire they sent around to the staff, about 100 people responded saying they wanted to have it discontinued.
But only 10 to 50 of them ever showed up.
So they've abandoned it again, which suggests to me that the place is too large.
Why did you stop teaching full time?
Well, I'm 67 years old.
I'm not teaching full time.
But I'm teaching in two places.
You mean stop teaching full-time?
Well, I all of a sudden see you drifting more and more into administration.
This is the sort of picture, maybe an erroneous picture.
You mean long ago?
Long ago, while you were at Scripps.
I see you all of a sudden director of two institutions almost simultaneously, Scripps and the University of California at La Jolla.
And I wondered if that didn't eliminate you teaching, and what was your reaction to that personally when that occurred?
I didn't mind it, but I was creating something.
I'm a good guy at beginning things, not necessarily a good guy at managing them after they've gone.
And what I was doing was transforming the Scripps Institution from a small, locally-oriented laboratory to a world-exploring
multidisciplinary activity.
And we ended up in 12 shifts when I was, the last year I was director.
Would you estimate that to be your major accomplishment while director of scripts, changing scripts from a localized institution to, may I call it a multiversity, that's the wrong choice of words.
I wouldn't use that word at all.
It became a world institution, concerned with the whole ocean, not just with the water that all of a sudden fell.
One way, if I had an epitaph as director of Scripps, I would say, he sent Scripps to sea.
Sort of like, I did the same thing at Scripps in some, I hope you won't think this is an egocentric comparison, but it illustrates what I'm talking about.
I did the same thing at Scripps that Prince Henry the Navigator did for Portugal.
I made it a world country instead of a little tit on the Iberian Peninsula.
I might add you chose the same words too, age of exploration, when you described what you thought the activities ought to be in the periods of the 17th century vis-a-vis the 1950s.
Was that deliberate?
How's that?
I'm sorry.
Well, I'm saying that you and Prince Henry, in effect, chose the same words.
He says age of exploration when he talks about his 17th century.
And you say age of exploration, in effect, when you talk about
about your century.
You're talking about Prince Henry the Navigator?
No, I'm talking about when you refer back to the time that began with Prince Henry and the time that closes on down through the 17th century.
You speak of that in terms of age of exploration.
Right, right.
And I'm saying in the decades of the 50s and the early 60s, you choose to use the same word.
That's right.
Was that deliberate?
That's right.
And if you ask a guy like Walter Monk, what kind of a guy I am, let's say I'm essentially an adventurer.
Much like these guys that sailed for Prince Henry.
He also calls you a naturalist.
Yeah.
At least in some of the things I read.
Which I assume is the same sort of thing in this sense.
Sort of a common interest about the world.
Well, what he means by that is that I was interested in and effective at describing things.
Not very good at
at experimentation or analysis.
I didn't have the mathematical background or the experimental skill.
But when it comes to knowing something about a lot of different things and being able to put it together and asking piercing or penetrating questions, that's always been my special knack.
And I've helped him a lot by, for example, by asking him questions about why he's doing what he's doing.
What does it mean?
Do you have any opinion on the relatively large crop of graduate students who are now appearing from the oceanographic institutions of the country?
You think there are too many coming out?
Too few?
Is this what you visioned for Scripps?
Well, I guess I'm worried about what happened to the astronomers.
You know, there are about 10 astronomers for every job in astronomy.
What are all these guys gonna do?
I don't know.
I don't either.
Sometimes I'll tell you what historians do.
Is a specialized school such as Texas A&M University
a good way to produce society's professionals?
Or should the school be more generalized in your concept and what you visualized it to be?
Well, I think that, as I said, the basic purpose of a university education should be to learn how to learn.
And that's not as simple as it sounds.
It means in the first place you need to learn the language.
I don't mean French and German.
I mean the language of your subject.
You need to believe that you can find out something that hasn't been found out before.
And you need to think it's fun to find out something that hasn't been found out before.
None of those say much about Brick.
Principle that you could do all three of those things and study nothing but physics.
The reason, but that's...
only part of it.
Another aspect of learning how to learn is to be interested in things.
And the way you get interested is to know something about them.
At least that's the way I get interested.
And therefore, I think people need to know something about a lot of different things and be interested.
Enough so they're interested.
Not necessarily enough so they're experts, but enough so
I think it would be nice to know more.
I'd like for the next series of questions
I should like for the next series of questions to concern theories of international cooperation.
You've done much in terms of this spirit of international cooperation.
Would you comment, please, upon some of these and what you feel about them?
What about NORPAC?
How did it develop your attitude towards it, and do you think international cooperation works?
Well, NORPAC was an idea of Joe Reed, who was a descriptive physical oceanographer.
And his idea was that we ought to get a kind of a photograph of the North Pacific Ocean, the water masses of the Pacific Ocean during one season and one year.
And in order to do that, we had to get a lot of ships out simultaneously.
And so we went to Japan.
I went to Japan, I guess.
I think somebody from the Office of Naval Research went with me.
I'm not quite sure about that.
I don't quite remember that.
And worked with the head of the hydrographic office.
in Japan, a nice little old man whose name slips my mind for the moment, and also with the fisheries people there.
And they arranged to have several of their ships take part in it.
And the Canadian Oceanographic Group in Nanaimo
under Tully took part also.
And the Bureau of Commercial Fisheries ships in Hawaii.
And we were able to produce them as a kind of an atlas of the North Pacific for that one time.
That's something that meteorologists do all the time.
They have synoptic weather maps.
But it's very difficult in oceanography because it's so much more difficult to make the observation.
You can make a map of ocean surface temperature, more or less, on merchant ships, at least along the routes that merchant ships travel.
But in many areas of the ocean where there aren't any merchant
And of course, they never stop and never take observation from the surface.
I guess this was the first international operation that we were engaged in here at Scripps.
There had been quite a bit of the same kind of thing in the Atlantic, sponsored by the International Council for the Exploration of the Sea.
And the man I told you about yesterday, Bjorn Helen Hansen,
had been involved with several of these multi-ship expeditions.

Then I guess the biggest cooperative venture of this kind was the International Indian Ocean Expedition, which was a project first proposed and out and detailed by the Scientific Committee of Oceanic Research.
which was appointed by the International Council of Scientific Unions in 1957, I think it was.
This is called SCOR, and it still exists, S-C-O-R. And the idea, I think the idea came first from Columbus Islam.
meeting at Woods Hole, first meeting, organizing meeting for SCORE and I was the president of it.

I was the first president of SCORE and presided at this organizing meeting and I sort of picked the, I did pick the members of SCORE and decided that Columbus would represent the International Geographical Union and George Deacon, the International Union of Geology and Geophysics and so forth.
Then the executive board of ICSI had been appointed to these people as representing the different unions.
I guess the unions had to be consulted, too.
There was a man named Bernicke from Germany who was the head of the German, civilian head of the German Hydrographic Office.
It was all civilian in those days.
In Germany, there was a
several European countries.
And of course, eventually, we had representatives from Australia, a man from Australia, George Humphreys, a man from Japan.
It was really an international committee, but representing not countries, but unions.
And there was a Russian member, Vladimir Vladimir Korg, who was their great exploring type oceanographer, physical oceanographer.
I think Zenkevich was a member, too.
Well, it's easy to find out who the members were, and I'm not sure that I
I can give you anywhere near a complete list of the first.
Anyhow, Columbus proposed at this meeting in Woods Hole that one large area which needed a lot more field work was the Indian Ocean.
It was the unknown ocean in 1957 and the way that the Atlantic and the Pacific were not.
And we all took this up with great, great enthusiasm.
And we appointed a coordinator, not an oceanographer at all, but a social scientist who had worked for the Navy for several years
as a project officer for the experimental testing unit of the Navy.
It was a fleet task force that tested equipment.
He'd been one of their project officers.
His name was Bob Snyder.
He traveled around the world.
drumming up enthusiasm for this big operation that we proposed in the Indian Ocean, getting ships and ship plans.
And altogether, they ended up with about 20 ships going to the Indian Ocean, doing different things.
Everybody telling everybody else what they were doing and putting together where they could.
We never had the kind of thing that we had at NORPAC, where everybody was out there simultaneously so we could get a picture of a physical oceanography.
Rather, it was a series of studies of particular phenomena.
For example, Johnny Knauss went out with his ship from Rhode Island and got
A couple of others, one of our ships involved, and two of our ships, I guess.
A study of whether there was an equatorial undercurrent, like the Cromwell current sitting in the Indian Ocean.
And the interesting thing about the circulation of the Indian Ocean is that it reverses itself every year.
Part of the time, the currents go west.
Part of the time, the currents go east because of the monsoon.
the wind-driven current.
And under those circumstances, Johnny's question was whether you would get an equatorial undercurrent.
Warren Wooster and Henry Stommel and the English group concentrated on the Somali current, which was a very fast, big current on the northeast side of Africa.
It's like the Gulf Stream, except even stronger and bigger because it's in low latitude.
And my car, the Oldsport, is quite weak.
And Bob Fisher and Bruce Hazen

Quite a few other people concentrated on the bottom, on the geology and geophysics, particularly on the bottom topography and the bottom sediments and geophysical measurements of the thickness of sediments and the depth through the moho and things like that.
So we ended up
Ten years later, or five, whatever the time when the most intense work was being done, I guess the early 60s was the most intense, the concentration of ships there.
Australians were involved and the Russians were very involved.
And we gradually built up quite a bit of cooperation with the Russians.
Particularly with the geophysicist, Udinsev.
U-D-I-N-T-S-E-V. U-D-I-N-T-S-E-V. We ended up at the end of about five or six years with two results.
One, that we knew an awful lot more about the Indian Ocean than we did before.
And the other is that there were a lot of oceanographers interested in it.
but they've been going there ever since.
Is the approach to oceanography quite similar in all these countries?

I know this is a difficult question to answer, but if you, for example, had to compare Australian, Russian, and American oceanographers, do you use about the same techniques, about the same tools, ask about the same sorts of questions?
Well, the Russians and the Americans,
Not the Australians.
The Russians and the three major oceanographic institutions in this country with all the modern scripts are big, multi-disciplinary, multi-purpose, multi-objective, heavily financed institutions.
And they send their ships out on these complex expeditions where they try to do as many things all at once.
That's also the technique the Russians have used.
And they're concerned basically with the world ocean.
Not so much with any particular part of it.
On the other hand, the Australians

have much less effort going into oceanography, much less emphasis on the operation, on the continuing operation of big ships, and more concerned with their part of the ocean, the waters around Australia, the waters around Australia.
very much more provincial.
The British and the Germans and the Japanese have operated much like we have, but they've had a special interest in
some parts of the ocean.
For example, the British have always had a great interest in the Antarctic, and the Japanese in areas where they catch fish, or where they hope they might catch fish.
The Germans in two areas, fishing
North Sea fisheries and the Indian and the tropical Atlantic.
These are scientific.
The French have, well the French have, you can't characterize the French very well because there are several groups.
in France, one of them led by Jacques Cousteau.
One, two, three, testing.
One, two, three, testing.
